  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT237-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">poruḷ muṟṟi mīḷvāṉ tērppākaṉukku (G2: tērppākaṟku) (C2, G2: uraippāṉāyt
          taṉ neñciṟku) uraittatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Told to the charioteer by him who returned after having
          achieved wealth. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT237">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l>añcuva taṟiyā tamartuṇai taḻīi</l>
          <l>neñcunap pirintaṉ ṟāyiṉu meñciya</l>
          <l>kaipiṇi nekiḻiṉaḵ tevaṉō naṉṟuñ</l>
          <l>cēya vamma viruvā miṭaiyē</l>
          <l>mākkaṭaṟ ṟiraiyiṉ muḻaṅki valaṉērpu</l>
          <l>kōṭpuli vaḻaṅkuñ cōlai</l>
          <l>yeṉaitteṉ ṟeṇṇukō muyakkiṭai malaivē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l rend="indent">Even if the heart has separated <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">pirintaṉṟu
            āyiṉum</term>: either the heart has actually made the way before HE himself can, or it
            is to be understood hypothetical: "even if the heart were to separate ...".</note> from
            us</l>
          <l rend="indent2">embracing the desirable mate</l>
          <l rend="indent6">without knowing of something fearful,</l>
          <l rend="indent">if [still] the bond becomes loose on the hand [of her]</l>
          <l rend="indent6">who has been left aside,</l>
          <l rend="indent8">what [good is] it?</l>
          <l>Much <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">naṉṟum</term> has once again to be
            understood as an adverb, though it is puzzling here, because one would rather expect an
            adjective (cf. KT 29.4, 226.3, 327.3).</note> the distances, <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">cēya</term> cannot but be read as the neuter pl. to <term xml:lang="ta">cēy</term> "distance" – is this the predicate noun of an nominal
            sentence with iṭai as a subject (thus also Cām.)?</note> alas, between us.</l>
          <l>How many do I count –</l>
          <l rend="indent">woods where killing tigers are roaming, rising</l>
          <l rend="indent2">powerfully <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">valaṉ</term> can be
            understood either adverbially or as a metonymic apposition: "a power rising [and]
            thundering ...".</note> [and] thundering like the waves of the great sea,</l>
          <l rend="indent7">obstacles between [our] embrace?</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
